Good morning. Thank you for looking over the amendments.







I will omit the amendment to the feasibility language. Although I cannot be=
 100% certain, it has not been my experience with members of the public inq=
uiring about public meetings that they are looking to the DC Register as as=
 the primary source of public body meetings. In practice, the public I have=
 encountered, always reference meetings and agenda listed not he public bod=
y website.




Regarding #2, all public bodies have the ability to, at minimum, record on =
audio via a digital recorder or through recording technology in "wired" roo=
ms across the city. The statute itself says "record by electronic means," s=
o OOG does not propose changing that language. Other than public bodies enc=
ountering technical issues with equipment, I have not received any feedback=
 from public bodies regarding an inability to record by way of audio. Nor d=
o I hear from public bodies as trainings that recording on audio is impract=
ical. The easiest form of compliance with "electronic means" is audio recor=
ding, as the cost of digital recorders are minimal and the city offers seve=
ral meeting locations where public bodies can record.




Additionally, the OOG has consistently interpreted the 3-business day requi=
rement as having being met with a publication of draft meeting minutes, bec=
ause public bodies do not convene every three days to finalize meeting minu=
tes. This way public bodies can meet the disclosure/transparency objectives=
 of the OMA, while not being under unreasonable time constraints to comply.




Perhaps we can finalize at the next board meeting, since the DC Register ha=
s returned the amendments for submission with the proper transmittal form?




Traci

